\\nu,\\rm near\nUV}$ correlation for strong AGNs. Otherwise, most nuclei are X-ray faint,\nconsistent with either a low-luminosity AGN or a nuclear X-ray binary\npopulation, and fall in the \"non-AGN locus\" in $\\alpha_{\\rm OX}-\\nu L_{\\nu,\\rm\nnear UV}$ space, which also hosts other, normal, galaxies. Our results suggest\nthat HCG X-ray nuclei in high specific star formation rate spiral galaxies are\nlikely dominated by star formation, while those with low specific star\nformation rates in earlier types likely harbor a weak AGN. The AGN fraction in\nHCG galaxies with $M_R \\le -20$ and $L_{X,{\\rm 0.5-8.0 keV}} \\ge 10^{41}$ erg\ns$^{-1}$ is $0.08^{+0.35}_{-0.01}$, somewhat higher than the $\\sim 5%$ fraction\nin galaxy clusters.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 15 Mar 2014 22:08:09 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-06-19"}
